result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Ty S Kearney was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Exposing Genitals/Pubic Area/Intimate Parts to a Child, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.10(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ty S Kearney in court with attorney Nicholas Frederick Gansner.  Brenda L. Yaskal appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Amended information filed by ADA Yaskal. Reading waived.  Rights/Elements.  Defendant pled no contest to Cts. 1 & 2.  On Count 1 Court withheld adjudication, approved DPA and terms.  On Count 2 Court found guilty.  Judgment was entered. Court withheld sentence, placed defendant on probation for 3 years.  Conditions of probation include: $518.00 costs.  $310.00 restitution plus surcharge.  Submit DNA sample.  Must attend and comply with sex offender treatment.  Atty Ganser requested that defendant no have to register as a sex offender as per agreement with ADA Yaskal, and requested that court find that a motor vehicle was not used in Ct. 2.  State took no position on request for finding in regards to Ct. 2.  State did agree, that at this time, the agreement is for defendant not to register as a sex offender, unless DPA is revoked on Ct. 1.  Court did not order the defendant to register as a sex offender, withheld the decision.  Defendant is to not be within 1000 feet of H.R.J.'s residence and no contact with H.J. R.  On Ct. 2 Court found a motor vehicle was not used.  1 day of jail credit.
